2500|$|<b>Geryon,</b> {{the winged}} monster who allows Dante and Virgil to descend a vast cliff {{to reach the}} Eighth Circle, was {{traditionally}} represented as a giant with three heads and three conjoined bodies. Dante's <b>Geryon,</b> meanwhile, is an image of fraud, combining human, bestial, and reptilian elements: <b>Geryon</b> is a [...] "monster with the general shape of a wyvern but with {{the tail of a}} scorpion, hairy arms, a gaudily-marked reptilian body, and the face of a just and honest man". The pleasant human face on this grotesque body evokes the insincere fraudster whose intentions [...] "behind the face" [...] are all monstrous, cold-blooded, and stinging with poison.|$|R
